# Commit style

Use Conventional Commits: `type(scope): short description`.

Types: `feat`, `fix`, `refactor`, `test`, `docs`, `chore`, `perf`.
Scope: the domain folder touched (`auth`, `tasks`, `board`, `analytics`, `k8s`).

When a commit fixes one of the deliberate edge cases from PROJECT_PLAN.md,
say so explicitly in the body, e.g.:

```
fix(tasks): prevent order collision on concurrent reorder

Two simultaneous PATCH /tasks/:id/reorder requests could read the same
order value before either write completed. Wrapped the read-modify-write
in a Prisma transaction with a re-read inside the transaction.
```

This turns the git history itself into interview material — a reviewer (or
you, months later) can see exactly which commits were "found and fixed a real
bug" versus routine feature work.
